[1mNAME[0m
       git-switch - Switch branches

[1mSYNOPSIS[0m
       [1mgit switch [22m[[4m<options>[24m] [[1m--no-guess[22m] [4m<branch>[0m
       [1mgit switch [22m[[4m<options>[24m] [1m--detach [22m[[4m<start-point>[24m]
       [1mgit switch [22m[[4m<options>[24m] ([1m-c[22m|[1m-C[22m) [4m<new-branch>[24m [[4m<start-point>[24m]
       [1mgit switch [22m[[4m<options>[24m] [1m--orphan [4m[22m<new-branch>[0m

[1mDESCRIPTION[0m
       Switch to a specified branch. The working tree and the index are updated to match the branch.
       All new commits will be added to the tip of this branch.

       Optionally a new branch could be created with either [1m-c[22m, [1m-C[22m, automatically from a remote
       branch of same name (see [1m--guess[22m), or detach the working tree from any branch with [1m--detach[22m,
       along with switching.

       Switching branches does not require a clean index and working tree (i.e. no differences
       compared to [1mHEAD[22m). The operation is aborted however if the operation leads to loss of local
       changes, unless told otherwise with [1m--discard-changes [22mor [1m--merge[22m.

[1mOPTIONS[0m
       [4m<branch>[0m
           Branch to switch to.

       [4m<new-branch>[0m
           Name for the new branch.

       [4m<start-point>[0m
           The starting point for the new branch. Specifying a [4m<start-point>[24m allows you to create a
           branch based on some other point in history than where [1mHEAD [22mcurrently points. (Or, in the
           case of [1m--detach[22m, allows you to inspect and detach from some other point.)

           You can use the [1m@[22m{-[4m<N>[24m} syntax to refer to the [4m<N>[24m-th last branch/commit switched to
           using [1mgit switch [22mor [1mgit checkout [22moperation. You may also specify [1m- [22mwhich is synonymous to
           [1m@[22m{-1}. This is often used to switch quickly between two branches, or to undo a branch
           switch by mistake.

           As a special case, you may use [4m<rev-a>[24m[1m...[4m[22m<rev-b>[24m as a shortcut for the merge base of
           [4m<rev-a>[24m and [4m<rev-b>[24m if there is exactly one merge base. You can leave out at most one of
           [4m<rev-a>[24m and [4m<rev-b>[24m, in which case it defaults to [1mHEAD[22m.

